  "prompt": "Did the participants in Plato's Academy call themselves students? How did Plato call them?",
  "response": "In Plato's Academy, participants did not typically refer to themselves as \"students\" in the modern sense. Instead, they were often called \"friends\" or \"companions.\" Plato himself referred to them in a more philosophical context, emphasizing the idea of philosophical inquiry and dialogue. The term \"philosopher\" was more aligned with the aspirations of those in the Academy, as the pursuit of wisdom was central to their identity. Thus, while they engaged in an educational process, their self-identification was more closely tied to friendship, companionship in learning, and the shared pursuit of wisdom rather than a formal student-teacher dynamic.",
